{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506396"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:42:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:42:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2535"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2535"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.48,0.06,0.06,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2535"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30618"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2535"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2535"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16561"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1964"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2437"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2439"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14580"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48457"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/30618"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA patient is undergoing rapid sequence intubation (RSI) after being brought in by ambulance with a GCS of 7 following a motor vehicle accident. From his most recent medical records the patient\u2019s height is 172cm tall and weight 130kgs. The decision is made to use ketamine for the RSI.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following should the dosage of ketamine be based on for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Actual body weight","Ideal body weight","Age based","BMI based","Height based"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMany drugs used in anaesthetics are based on weight calculations. However, there comes an additional level of difficulty when the patient\u2019s weight is above expected for their height. \u003Cstrong\u003EIdeal body weight\u003C/strong\u003E can be calculated by 22 x (patients height in meters^2) or simplified to Height \u2013 100 in males or height \u2013 110 in females. In this case the patient\u2019s ideal body weight would be between 65-72kgs. This means there is a large difference between his ideal body weight and actual, hence this can have a huge influence on the drug dosages. His BMI can also be calculated to be 44.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no clear clinical evidence around the dosing of medications in critical care in obese patients. The volume of distribution and clearance of medication, as well as whether they are lipophilic or lipophobic are all influence by a patient\u2019s body weight. Overall, ideal body weight or adjusted body weight for initial doses is appropriate, especially if their BMI exceeds 40. This prevents large doses, supratherapeutic sedation and potential side effects occurring. Ketamine and propofol dosing is recommended to be based on ideal body weight (IBW) rather than actual body weight (ABW), especially in patients with a BMI \u0026gt;40. Age based, BMI based or height based would not be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ideal body weight should be calculated in obese patients to dose some medications","Ideal body weight = 22 x (patients height^2)"],"references":["Erstad, B.L., Barletta, J.F. Drug dosing in the critically ill obese patient\u2014a focus on sedation, analgesia, and delirium. Crit Care 24, 315 (2020). https://doi.org/10.1186/s13054-020-03040-z","Olivier Moreault, Yves Lacasse, Jean S. Bussi\u00e8res; Calculating Ideal Body Weight: Keep It Simple. Anesthesiology 2017; 127:203\u2013204 doi: https://doi.org/10.1097/ALN.0000000000001687","Nickson, C, 2020. Rapid Sequence Intubation (RSI). Life in the fast lane. Available: https://litfl.com/rapid-sequence-intubation-rsi/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16561"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2535"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/16561"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-12-06T10:10:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-30T10:50:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2535"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30618"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attribu